PANDAS - Numpy and Series¶

Numpy¶

Numpy is Numerical Python

It is a Scientific computing Library

The Fundamental Data Structure is the n-dimensional Array

An n-dimensional Array is a collection of elements.

In [182]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
In [183]:
my_array = np.array([10 , 20 , 20 , 30 , 40 , 50])
In [184]:
#Applying map function on an Array of numbers or a List of Numbers
#Multiply all the numbers by 10

arr = []

for i in my_array:
    arr.append(i * 10)
In [185]:
arr
Out[185]:
[100, 200, 200, 300, 400, 500]

Alternatively we can use the "map" function for the same thing¶

map() is a Python Funciton that works as an Iterator to return a result after applying a function to every item of an iterable (tuple, lists, etc).

It is used when you want to apply a single transformation to all the iterable elements.

The Iterable and and Function are passed as arguments to the map in Python

In [186]:
#Creating a map object

map(lambda i : i * 10 , my_array)
Out[186]:
<map at 0x276f4b7a070>
In [187]:
#Getting the output in a List

list(map(lambda i : i * 10 , my_array))
Out[187]:
[100, 200, 200, 300, 400, 500]
In [188]:
#Getting the output in a Tuple

tuple(map(lambda i : i * 10 , my_array))
Out[188]:
(100, 200, 200, 300, 400, 500)
In [189]:
#Getting the Output in a Set

set(map(lambda i : i * 10 , my_array))  #A Set will not have any duplicate values, hence you see "200" just once
Out[189]:
{100, 200, 300, 400, 500}

Most Pythonic way to do this :¶

In [190]:
#A List comprehension

[ i * 10 for i in my_array]
Out[190]:
[100, 200, 200, 300, 400, 500]
In [191]:
#In Python we saw many ways to do this
#But in Numpy Array , its as simple as saying:

my_array * 10
Out[191]:
array([100, 200, 200, 300, 400, 500])

Numpy offers a wide range of functions that are otherwise unavailable in python

Numpy Arrays are much more efficient then Python Lists

trade off : Numpy Arrays contain only one Data Type

In [192]:
test_array = np.array([1 , 0.2  , 3])
In [193]:
test_array.dtype #All other int has also been converted to Float
Out[193]:
dtype('float64')
In [194]:
test_array  = np.array([1 , 'dog'  , 3])
In [195]:
#This is known as Implicit Upcasting
In [196]:
test_array  #All int has been converted to String
Out[196]:
array(['1', 'dog', '3'], dtype='<U11')

Hence , Numpy makes sure all elements are of same data type

Pandas Series¶

Series are :¶

  • One- dimensional
  • Labelled Arrays
  • Any Data Type

or said differently¶

  • A sequence of values with associated Labels
In [197]:
students = ['Andrew' , 'Brie' , 'Kanika']
In [198]:
type(students)
Out[198]:
list

In order to generate a Pandas Series out of this Python List , we simply use this Series constructor which is available in the Pandas Module and we pass the List as an Argument.

In [199]:
pd.Series(students)
Out[199]:
0    Andrew
1      Brie
2    Kanika
dtype: object
In [200]:
ages = [27 , 49  , 37]
In [201]:
pd.Series(ages)
Out[201]:
0    27
1    49
2    37
dtype: int64
In [202]:
heights = [167.4 , 173.2 , 190.0]
In [203]:
pd.Series(heights)
Out[203]:
0    167.4
1    173.2
2    190.0
dtype: float64

Pandas Series supports mixed Data types

In [204]:
mixed = [True , 'Say' , {'my_mood' : 100}]
In [205]:
pd.Series(mixed)
Out[205]:
0                True
1                 Say
2    {'my_mood': 100}
dtype: object

Parameters VS Arguments¶

Above we were passing Pandas List as Argument to the "data" parameter

pd.Series(mixed)

or

pd.Series(data = mixed)

Arguments are the actual values that we associate with the Parameters

In [206]:
def greeting(something):
    print(something)
In [207]:
greeting("Good Morning to you")

Good Morning to you

INDEX and RANGEINDEX¶

In the above examples you noticed that Pandas automatically generated the Index for us when we created the Series.

Pandas Index starts at 0 and ends at an Integer that is one less than the length of the Series.

In [222]:
#example
age = pd.Series(ages , dtype = 'float')
In [223]:
len(age)
Out[223]:
3
In [224]:
#The length of the series is 3 but the Index is ending at len(age) - 1 , that is "2"

age
Out[224]:
0    29.0
1    47.0
2    34.0
dtype: float64
In [225]:
#Creating a Brand New Series that contains our Custom labels

books_list = ['Harry Potter' , 'Panda' , 'Sci-Fi']
In [226]:
pd.Series(data = books_list , index = ['FICTION' , 'COMEDY' , 'ADVENTURE'])
Out[226]:
FICTION      Harry Potter
COMEDY              Panda
ADVENTURE          Sci-Fi
dtype: object

OR¶

Out[227]:

COMEDY              Panda
ADVENTURE          Sci-Fi
dtype: object

Method VS Attribute¶

ATTRIBUTE : An Attribute is a Variable bound to the Object

METHOD : A Method is a Function bound to the object

In [240]:
#Example of an Attribute
#We are accessing a property bound to the Object

books_series.size
Out[240]:
3
In [241]:
#Example of a Method

list_s.equals(dict_s)
Out[241]:
True
In [242]:
#Example of an Attribute
#We are accessing a property bound to the Object
list_s.dtype
Out[242]:
dtype('O')

Another Solution¶

In [271]:
#This is is list
actor_names
Out[271]:
['james', 'Angelina', 'Lina', 'Mary']
In [272]:
actor_ages
Out[272]:
[25, 31, 45, 33]
In [273]:
#we unpack the output of the zip function 
{name : age for name , age in zip(actor_names , actor_ages)}
Out[273]:
{'james': 25, 'Angelina': 31, 'Lina': 45, 'Mary': 33}
In [274]:
#Now we know the above code works
#We can go ahead and create a Series

pd.Series({name : age for name , age in zip(actor_names , actor_ages)})
Out[274]:
james       25
Angelina    31
Lina        45
Mary        33
dtype: int64

map()¶

Python's map() is a built-in function that allows you to process and transform all the items in an iterable without using an explicit for loop, a technique commonly known as mapping. map() is useful when you need to apply a transformation function to each item in an iterable and transform them into a new iterable.

In [357]:
#We use the map() function to append "label_" to each element of the Index
#We edit this same code : labeled_alphabet = pd.Series(data = list(ascii_lowercase) , index = list(ascii_uppercase))
labeled_alphabet = pd.Series(data = list(ascii_lowercase), index = map(lambda x: 'label_' + x, list(ascii_uppercase)))
In [359]:
labeled_alphabet.head(3)
Out[359]:
label_A    a
label_B    b
label_C    c
dtype: object

Out[383]:

Difference between Position Indexing and Label Indexing

  • When we access the value using psition Index , for example [0:3] , 3 is excluded
  • Whereas , in the Label Indexing , when we say , go from the beginning to "label_C" --->"labeled_alphabet[:'label_C']" "label_C" is actually included

Question:¶

  • Why do we have two different ways to achieve the same thing then?

Label based indexing is a little slower than .loc

  • Comparitively loc is a more robust way or Pythonic way of doing Label based Extraction

Both loc and regular slicing supports Boolean arrays or boolean Masks

In [ ]:
#boolean
#We can create a list of Booleans for specifying what values we want to extract from a given Series

Note : The Length of the mask should match the length of the Series¶

  • But if your series had some 1000 items , then you won't be sitting and typing 1000 booleans
  • In that case we generate Boolean Mask and pass it to the square brackets

Using Callables with .loc and .iloc¶

Indexing with Callables¶

  • Used for highly customizable Indexing
  • Work with [], .loc and .iloc
  • A single-argument function that returns indexing output
  • A Callable is just an Object that accepts some argument and possibly returns something back
  • classes in Python are technically "Callables"
  • The simplest and best example is a Function
  • Our function here will take a Series as an Input and it will produce an Indexing Output.
  • Indexing Output : "A list of Labels" , "List of Booleans" , "A Slice" etc
  • The difference here is we will be using a function to generate the Indexing

Example : Extracting a Single Label¶

In [457]:
#Without using a Callable
labeled_alphabet.loc['label_V']
Out[457]:
'v'
In [458]:
#Using a Callable
#Here , within the loc indexer, we have a Anonymous Lambda function that accepts a Single Argument which is always the
#Series itself
#So think of "x" as the series always
labeled_alphabet.loc[lambda x: 'label_V']
Out[458]:
'v'
In [459]:
#Lets work with a Python list capturing two labels

labeled_alphabet.loc[lambda x: ['label_V' , 'label_A']]
Out[459]:
label_V    v
label_A    a
dtype: object
In [460]:
#Lets check with Boolean Mask
#Im accessing the size attribute of the Series
#Generating a range of numbers 
#For each of those numbers , inserting a True in the resulting list , which is returned by the lambda function

labeled_alphabet.loc[lambda x: [True for i in range(x.size)]]
Out[460]:
label_A    a
label_B    b
label_C    c
label_D    d
label_E    e
label_F    f
label_G    g
label_H    h
label_I    i
label_J    j
label_K    k
label_L    l
label_M    m
label_N    n
label_O    o
label_P    p
label_Q    q
label_R    r
label_S    s
label_T    t
label_U    u
label_V    v
label_W    w
label_X    x
label_Y    y
label_Z    z
dtype: object
In [470]:
#Defining a Function

def every_fifth(x):
    return [True if i%5==0 else False for i in range(x.size)]
In [471]:
#We pass this function to the iloc indexer

labeled_alphabet.iloc[every_fifth]
Out[471]:
label_A    a
label_F    f
label_K    k
label_P    p
label_U    u
label_Z    z
dtype: object
In [472]:
#Lets say , we want to start from e instead of a

def every_fifth(x):
    return[True if (i+1)%5==0 else False for i in range(x.size)]
In [473]:
#We pass this function to the iloc indexer

labeled_alphabet.iloc[every_fifth]
Out[473]:
label_E    e
label_J    j
label_O    o
label_T    t
label_Y    y
dtype: object

So , we saw above that , it is possible to use a Callable to produce indexing output. -This opens a window of possibilities because its highly flexible and Customisable.

.get() method¶

Another way to extract values from a Series is the .get() method

In [475]:
#get() also follows Label based indexing like loc
In [474]:
labeled_alphabet.get('label_I')
Out[474]:
'i'
In [476]:
labeled_alphabet.loc['label_I']
Out[476]:
'i'
In [477]:
labeled_alphabet['label_I']
Out[477]:
'i'

Q: Why should we use get() when we have the other two methods?¶

get() method has some conveniences to offer

In [478]:
#get() seems to return nothing when we try to access a index label that does not exist
labeled_alphabet.get('label_inexistent')
In [479]:
#Infact it is actually returning the object "None"

labeled_alphabet.get('label_inexistent') == None
Out[479]:
True

This is because get() supports a default parameter , which by default is assigned to the object "None"

In [480]:
labeled_alphabet.get('label_inexistent' , default = None)

This is great because it gives us the opportunity to specify a Custom default value.

  • So when a label is not found the msg is displayed
In [481]:
labeled_alphabet.get('label_inexistent' , default = "Could not find the Label")
Out[481]:
'Could not find the Label'
In [482]:
#We could index by position as well same like iloc and regular Square bracket indexing
#get() method does not have Slice support
labeled_alphabet.get(8)
Out[482]:
'i'
